Happy 4th! Enjoyed past week in Houston debriefing with Max, Oleg, Soichi, &TJ. Was good to have Exp 22 together again back on Earth!
For those in the DC area, I will be presenting at the Air&Space Museum this Thurs at 11am & 1pm in Gallery 113  http://ow.ly/1JSLU
http://bit.ly/3BNZQi  Here's what happened...
Congratulations to the Orion Pad Abort test team...looked like one wild ride!
Finally! Mission debriefings are complete, reconditioning program has left me feeling strong, and free time is on the horizon.
Settled in back in Houston. Debriefings and reconditioning going well. Feeling very good. Great to be with family. Good to be home.
We're off, departing Star City, for the long day flying home to Houston! Meanwhile, Tracy, Sasha, and Misha prepare for launch at Baikonur.
The med tests show the new resistive exercise on ISS is working-good news! One more full day here in Russia and fly to Houston Thursday!
Just woke up. More med tests and rehab this AM. Feeling stronger every day. Hint of spring here. Lots of melting snow and sun expected.
Finally got a good night's sleep. Med experiments continue. Russian press conference today.3 days until departing for Houston. Feeling good.
We made it to Russia after 30 hour day. Fighting gravity but doing well.Med tests and rehab.Still winter in Star City. Need some sleep.
This is it. Thanks for support, encouragement and prayers. See you on the ground!
We will leave ISS in the good and capable hands of Oleg, Soichi, and TJ as they begin Expedition 23. "Sail" her well, guys!
Final prep today as we conclude Exp22. Thanks to the ground teams around the globe for a great mission bringing ISS toward full utilization.
Personal items packed for later Shuttle return, our Soyuz nearly ready, we're ready, change-of-command tomorrow.
Finished testing our Soyuz flight control system. Later, refresher on deorbit & entry procedures.SAR team deploying to Kazakhstan.
This week we broke my old Exp 13 record for number of Earth photos. Later, after landing and recovery, I will post some of best.
Big day for Japanese robitics system; "Small Fine Arm" deploy and checkout. Soichi and TJ at the controls.
@Phil_Johnson_Sorry you couldn't make it.  Get well soon!
One week to go until landing in Kazakhstan! Soyuz packing and entry procedure review. And we fixed the toilet! Electronics problem.
Just had a great pass up the East Coast USA. Beautiful sun glint highlighting Chesapeake Bay and from Long Island to Cape Cod.
We got through the day, mostly successful, except for that toilet repair. Still working on it. Good thing we have two of them.
toilet repair (always untimely), blood draw for experiment, plant experiment, and handover ops in prep for next weeks change-of-command.
Starting last full week on orbit for Max and me. Coming up, leak checks of our Sokol pressure suits in Soyuz.
Saturday activities: ISS maintenance, Earth obs, and the SPHERES experiment-among my favorites. http://ssl.mit.edu/spheres/
Congrats to ISS Program and Team for winning the National Aeronautic Association's Collier Award!!
Today, exercise of course. Also Station maintenance, press conference, and heart ultrasound (experiment).
Just passed over Chili. Many ships visible off the coast likely supporting relief efforts. Photos being downlinked to MCC.
Today experiments, stowage reorg, med exam, H2O recycle system maintenance, and... beginning of departure prep!
Completed leak check of new Tranquility module. Started 48 hour heart experiment. Later, emergency depress drill w/ entire crew.
Just had another pass over Patagonia. Clear skies (rare). Among my favorite glaciers in the world.
Today full of experiments for us; blood draws, blood pressure monitor, cardio measurements, bone study, diet study; but first, exercise.
19 days to go until landing in Kazakhstan in our Soyuz; then another week before returning to Houston!
While "enduring the agony" of the daily treadmill run, listened to a wonderful message on the "race of faith" in Hebrews 12. Encouraged!
Quiet Saturday. Starting to get organized for packing personal items for return to Earth.
Conducting my final session of VO2max experiment; max effort on bike; painful but experiment I'm very interested in.
"weight" lifted; donned heart monitor for experiment; conducting a couple other experiments. 3 weeks to go until landing!
Wrapping up a relatively light day. Our exercise machine broke so spent the afternoon fixing it...back in business.
Was up in the night to watch an East Coast and North Atlantic pass. Saw a couple of meteorites pass below and in front of us. Spectacular!
Great to see our friends on Endeavour safely back on Earth-congrats to the STS-130 crew on a great mission!
We worked through a little excitement today-command & control computer failure and loss of communication-4 times! All quiet now.
Done with daily exercise; lifting and running. Time to cleanup and have some breakfast.Then back to getting things ship-shape.
In the middle of a long sleep period, shifting back to GMT. Then couple of days off.We need the rest. Much to do in coming weeks.
We are now starting to get things back in order on ISS after the huge reconfiguration. Undocking coming soon.
The hatches are closed.Quiet on Station.Joint mission accomplished.STS-130 undocks tomorrow and we continue with Expedition 22.Now sleep.
Final day with STS130 crew on board. We'll have a farewell this afternoon.
...and no worries...we take lots of photos. Search astronaut earth photography and check mission highlights for Expedition 21&22.
We'll be getting the Cupola windows open today and have an even better view...the new window on the world! Stay tuned!
Great pass over Patagonia! First time I've seen it completely clear. Absolutely beautiful glaciers.
Be sure to check out CBS News today and the "Everyone in the World Has a Story" series. I hear we're on.
The Cupola is in it's final location and tomorrow we'll finish out the inside, the next day the outside, and then open it for business!
We've worked thru the issues and have a go to move the Cupola today... great news!
The new module looks great! Lunch break...now back to work!
Up to start the day. Today we ingress the new module and get it up and running. Great to have everybody on board!
Most of day's work complete.We'll brief tomorrow's spacewalk and then get Bob and Nick in the airlock for "campout." All's going well.
Off to the races today; working on water processing repairs, space suit repairs, and spacewalk prep. Of course, supplies transfer , too.
We're off to a great joint docked mission.As expected, like a beehive here. I love it!
Endeavour about 4000 ft away. Sunrise coming in a minute...heading to the window to photograph the heat shield for inspection.
Docking day! We have visual contact with Endeavour trailing behind us. This is my 4th Shuttle visit-1st for Endeavour!
Repressurized shuttle docking port. Preparations on ISS  going well. Lots of robotics and EVA coming after docking tomorrow..
Busy day today. It was great to see Endeavour get off the pad. Docking preparations tomorrow. Time now to get some sleep.
Repairing one of the systems that insure the air is safe-"Major Constituent Analyser"-just like I'm back in my garage!
Scrubbed for wx. Likely try again tomorrow. That's space 'biz! We on ISS now have some extra prep time.
Our friends are strapped in and ready. Launch in about 1 hr 20 min. We'll be flying over Indian Ocean when Shuttle lifts off.
Sunday morning. Relaxing a bit today except for some "housekeeping" items and exercise. Looking forward to seeing a Shuttle launch!
Max reminded me that he and I have just 40 days to go until we return to Kazakhstan. Looks cold there now but spring is in the air!
The plumbing job is complete. We have water! Here's a toast to the engineers who planned the fix!
Our week is over.Some Saturday work to go but then need to get some rest for Shuttle arrival. Be sure to follow their launch on Sunday.
Progress docking went well.Max opened the hatch to the smell of fresh fruit. Rarely enjoyed an apple as much as today-simple gifts!
Completed heart ultrasound as part of ongoing experiment. Now on to running on treadmill.
troubleshooting our water system today; also getting ready for Progress arrival tomorrow--fresh fruit on the way!
Normal day on ISS: prep'd the Airlock,deactivated an experiment, exercised, even watched some recorded news to catch up on earth.
ISS live video going to web starting today about 08:00 CST; separate from NASA TV. Welcome aboard!
We had a good conference with the STS-130 crew this AM. Plans in place for a great docked mission.
Today is day 125 for this flight...40 some to go! Donned a holter monitor for 48 hr experiment. Not very comfortable but good experiment.
Check out last week's reboost of the ISS orbit...  http://tinyurl.com/yczre36
First thing I did on internet? Order my wife some flowers.  They arrived a few days ago. It was a hit. Commerce from space!
Great Saturday on board ISS. Taking photos of Earth, preparing for Shuttle arrival, Station maintenance, and calls home.
Anybody know which planet is closely following the sun? It becomes visible to us when sun sets. Likely Venus but that's a guess.
Up early this AM. Great views of noctilucent clouds. Amazingly beautiful. Never tire of viewing part of God's creation we call Earth!
Great pass over Hawaii just now...Oregon in a couple minutes.
Great day on orbit.Day 118 for Max & me. Less tan 60 to go! Just finished exercise. Great photos of Sahara earlier.Passing over New Zealand.
Day off today gave us time to Expspend on web.It's great to be in touch again!We'll call today the ISS internet grand opening!
We had a reboost this morning preparing for Shuttle. Look for video showing what it's like to ride the reboost. Will get it to earth today.
Super robotics ops w/ Soichi and TJ today, getting ready for Shuttle arrival..Video available soon.
OK everybody..here's my first tweet from ISS. It's good to be on line! Appreciate the great job of the team who made it work!
3Jan; 21:20; Happy New Year from ISS. Still working on internet access so Tweeting via email. Hopefully, direct soon.
28Dec09 10:30GMT, Belated Merry Christmas. Happy New Year from ISS! Looking forward to 2010.
17Dec09 17:30 GMT  Check out this video to get a sense for flying through ISS. http://tinyurl.com/yb3gaqf #onorbit
17Dec09 16:30GMT I’m back after a break.Trying to get internet working on ISS to Twitter directly. Hopefully soon. Stay tuned. #onorbit
Good to see Nicole return to her family. #onorbit
25Nov09 12:30 GMT; Great docked mission complete. Sad to see our friends leave and drift back over the horizon. #onorbit
18Nov09,20:00GMT; Shuttle crew on board. Off to the races with EVA, Robotics and wrench turning! #onorbit
18Nov,0930GMT, Atlantis arriving today bearing gifts.Always an amazing sight out window.Will be good to see our friends! #onorbit
http://twitpic.com/pb7nr - 12Nov09 18:30GMT; Great day! New Russian module successful docked. ISS grew a little today. Working on opening ha
11Oct09 20:30 GMT; just finished call w/the Shuttle crew. Last minute plans. Will b good to have them onboard nxt week. www.nasa.gov/shuttle
8Nov09 17:30 GMT Relaxing day today; catching up on email & photos; Veterans Day this wk; thank a veteran! #onorbit
30 Oct09 GMT16:55 We have the HTV off ISS and hanging on the Arm. To be released shortly. #onorbit
29Oct09 GMT22:00 Got the HTV loaded with trash and hatch closed. Tomorrow we let it go and send it to burn up in the atmosphere! #onorbit
28Oct09 GMT08:20 Today I’m an IT guy, programming new laptops between weight lifting sets. Faster computers always better! #onorbit
25 Oct 09 GMT 18:00 Enjoyed a relaxing Sunday. First free day since launch.  Tomorrow, back to high pace of things.Busy week coming.#onorbit
Oct 09 16:45GMT Wiring myself up for cardiovascular experiment. Discomfort for 48 hrs but interesting experiment. #onorbit
21 Oct 09 15:45GMT Great Twitter event today! Thanks for being part of it. Sorry about the false smoke alarm. All is OK on-board. #onorbit
18Oct09 01:45 GMT  Progress 35 has docked to ISS. Fresh fruit and vegetables included. A few hours to go to get thru checks and hatch open.
16 Oct 09 GMT 16:25; Check out heavens-above.com to see when we are visible flying overhead your location. http://ow.ly/uSGx
Really no such thing as day off here. It’s all good though.
16 Oct 09 GMT 16:00; “Day off” today because we’ll be working over the weekend docking a Progress. #onorbit
13 Oct 09 21:00 GMT Took this photo of a lg plume from Montserrat Island in the Caribbean. Can you tell me what it is? http://ow.ly/uGll
14 Oct 09 22:00 GMT Long day today doing experiments, unloading HTV, and ISS maintenance. Ready for sleep. #onorbit
13 Oct 09 GMT 12:30; Performed heart ultrasound as part of an experiment. Got great shots of Sahara Desert-amazing place from here. #onorbit
11 Oct 09 GMT 04:45 After a 20 hour day, we got the Soyuz TMA-14 crew safely back on the ground. Tomorrow rest! http://ow.ly/tQXC #onorbit
11 Oct 09 13:55 Repaired exercise equipment-important and performing plumbing repair-very important.  #onorbit
9 Oct 11:35 GMT: We have the change-of-command today to end Exp. 20 & begin Exp. 21. http://ow.ly/tC16  Settled in-seems like I never left!
More info: on the C.O.L.B.E.R.T. treadmill can be found here: http://ow.ly/tBZt
8 Oct 22:20 GMT: time for sleep. Great day today. Among other things did a check out of new treadmill. Next test is running on it! #onorbit
8 Oct 14:30 GMT  Getting ready to operate the new treadmill for the first time. Can’t run on it until we test it out. #onorbit
7 Oct 22:20 GMT: Tomorrow will be gym day. Start resistive exercise and test out new treadmill. #onorbit
7 Oct 22:15 GMT: We enjoyed a great dinner tonight. Great crew dynamics on board. Tomorrow another busy day. #onorbit
GMT 279/18:30: Busy day working on new experiment facility and EVA tools. Of course, got some earth photography in as well. #onorbit
Here's the working link to video of me arriving on the station - http://ow.ly/sOUe
#onorbit: After two day flight, we docked and are getting settled in on ISS. Still an amazing place! http://ow.ly/sOfp
Breakfast done. Off we go. See you after docking. Thank you for prayers and support. Enjoy the journey! sdg
Off to breakfast...last meal for awhile where the food behaves well on the plate. Everybody is happy and calm.
And another from the past few days... http://ow.ly/rK0p
Here's some footage of training from the past month to set the stage. http://ow.ly/rJXW
Launch day!! Wakeup
Off to sleep.We'll wake on launch day.This may be last prelaunch post. Will pick up again after docking.Thank you for following!
Heading to final Commission for readiness, then press conference, then traditional movie. http://ow.ly/ry62
L-1! Rocket's ready. Spacecraft's ready. Family's ready. We're ready!  Grateful for your prayers and encouragement. Thank you!
Here's a web site here w articles, photos, NASA TV, and other info... http://spacelaunchnews.com/
Here's another training clip from July. check it out. http://ow.ly/rxfK
More photos of rollout from this morning. Amazing how quick they put it together and get it from barn to pad! http://ow.ly/rnLm
Our rocket is on the pad and ready to go! http://ow.ly/rnGW
Here are some photos documenting the past few days leading up to rollout.  http://ow.ly/rl69
Our rocket is rolling out to the launch pad now. Here's what it looks like. http://ow.ly/rkXJ
Our families will land in Baikonur within 15 minutes. The energy level is up with everybody. The next couple of days tend to fly by!
Awake before sunrise. L-3. Day off. Familys/friends arrive in Baikonur later today from Moscow. prep continues; http://ow.ly/regd
Lot's going on in space business! Some work; some play. http://ow.ly/r4j6 Tomorrow we go see our rocket. More prep work.
http://twitpic.com/j29o7 - By the way, check out the hat on this guy we ran into yesterday.
Check here for on-line viewing of our launch (30Sep)and docking(2Oct). Live vis internet. http://ow.ly/r1Vm
